{
  "texts": [
    "The availability of open-source large language models (LLMs) brings down the cost of generating content, creating opportunities for malicious actors to spread misleading content and influence public opinion [10,11].",
    "Worse yet, LLMs' ability to mimic writing styles makes this type of content persuasive yet very challenging to detect [12].In this paper, we propose several methods to infer the credibility of news-sharing accounts on social media to detect low-credibility accounts likely to spread misinformation.",
    "The credibility of a news source or account may depend on many factors, including reputation and adherence to factual reporting and transparency.",
    "More precisely, we define highcredibility news sources to be those that meet objective journalistic criteria as assessed by third-party fact-checking organizations [13,14].",
    "Following that, credible accounts are those who share or reshare high-credibility sources."
  ]
}